reviews.review_text:
hard-wired in my head This Hartford show has a very rich sound, little to not like on the quality of recording.  Soundboard.

For me, this was the first Dead show I ever went to, and the only one I failed to get into.  First trips that night too.  It was a miracle I made it back home with my friends.

In 1986, I had this cassette tape, listened to it tons.  Today was my first re-listen in 20 years.  Amazing how I could remember all the nuances in Drums/Space.  These shows get hard-wired in my head, all of them.  

Awesome Don't Need Love from Brent.  Enjoy.

Buried treasure This is one of the better Oade audiences IMO.  I am surprised that there is not more interest in this show.  It has a solid 1st set with a nice Bird Song and a very cool Supplication into a hot Let it Grow.

For the 2nd set there are a few slips, but overall a really nice bunch of spacey jams.   Phil thumps the whole show to everyone's delight.  You do have to deal with a Don't Need Love that deteriorates into a rather humorous drunken ending.  Oh, wait, you don't have to deal with it if you don't want (Jerry didn't) - you just hit those two little R. arrows.  Drums & space are nice but afterwards Jerry is clearly the voice of sobriety.  Still some solid material and a Wharf Rat that is no doubt for Brent.

Enjoy this one for what it is - a good representation of 1986 and some nice Jerry and Phil work couched in a very sweet sounding audience which sounds like a board in more than one spot.

LAtvala!

hot mingle, hot 1set, hot let it grow 1st show 4 me, aiko opener, check out 7/6/87 aiko
